On the average of the polls drawn up by <a href="https://twitter.com/POLITICOEurope?ref_src=twsrc%5Etfw">@POLITICOEurope</a> CDU-CSU is at the head with 29% against 21% of AfD. Both parties would grow compared to 2021, while all three forces of the Green Government Scholz <a href="https://t.co/Zn63VK1h7z">pic.twitter.com/Zn63VK1h7z</a> — Youtrend (@you_trend)
<a href="https://twitter.com/you_trend/status/1892254447356547302?ref_src=twsrc%5Etfw">February 19, 2025</a>
</blockquote
To speak of the direct effect of US political events on the public opinion of a European country as ours may seem a force, but so it is not. This is an example of Germany, where this Sunday will vote for the legislative elections and where the far-right party AfD (Alternative for Germany) is second in the polls with more than 20% of the consents. A “accompanied” growth (if not even favored) by the unleashed support of Elon Musk> and the impact that its social platform X (fu Twitter) has had on the media agenda for these last months.
&nbsp;
<div </div
